---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../../../styles/global.css";

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Guides", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "ACC Earner's Levy", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/acc-levy/" }
  ]
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is the ACC Earner's Levy the only ACC levy I pay?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "As an employee, the Earner's Levy is the only ACC levy deducted from your pay. Your employer also pays a separate ACC Work Levy and a Working Safer Levy, but these are business costs and do not appear on your payslip. If you are self-employed, you pay both the Earner's Levy and a Work Levy based on your industry's risk classification."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I opt out of ACC?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No, you cannot opt out of the ACC scheme. It is a compulsory, universal system that covers everyone in New Zealand, including visitors. The Earner's Levy is a mandatory deduction from your pay. In return, you receive comprehensive no-fault personal injury cover regardless of how or where an injury occurs."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does ACC cover in New Zealand?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "ACC covers the costs of treatment and rehabilitation for personal injuries, regardless of how they happened. This includes workplace injuries, sports injuries, accidents at home, car accidents, and more. ACC pays for medical treatment, surgery, physiotherapy, prescriptions, and other rehabilitation costs. If you cannot work due to your injury, ACC provides weekly compensation at 80% of your pre-injury earnings (up to a cap) after the first week."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="ACC Earner's Levy: What It Is & How It's Calculated | TakeHomePay.nz"
  description="Learn about the ACC Earner's Levy in New Zealand. How the 1.60% levy is calculated, the earnings cap, what ACC covers, and how it appears on your payslip."
  canonical="/guides/acc-levy/"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary to-primary-light py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-white">ACC Earner's Levy: What It Is & How It's Calculated</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-white/90">Understanding New Zealand's universal injury cover and the levy that funds it.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-8 text-sm text-text-muted">
        <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 flex-wrap">
          <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Home</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border font-medium text-text">ACC Earner's Levy</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          If you have ever looked at a New Zealand payslip, you will have noticed a deduction labelled something like "ACC Earner's Levy" or simply "ACC". This is a compulsory contribution that every employee in New Zealand pays towards the Accident Compensation Corporation's universal personal injury scheme. It is one of several standard deductions alongside PAYE income tax, KiwiSaver contributions, and student loan repayments.
        </p>

        <p>
          Unlike many countries where you need private insurance or rely on legal action to cover injury costs, New Zealand has a unique no-fault accident compensation scheme that covers everyone. This guide explains what the ACC Earner's Levy is, how it is calculated, what it pays for, and how the scheme works in practice for New Zealand workers.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">What Is ACC?</h2>

        <p>
          The Accident Compensation Corporation, known simply as ACC, is a New Zealand government entity that provides comprehensive, no-fault personal injury cover to all New Zealand residents and visitors. The scheme was established in 1974 following the recommendations of the Woodhouse Report, which proposed replacing the common law right to sue for personal injury with a comprehensive state-run accident compensation system.
        </p>

        <p>
          The "no-fault" principle is central to ACC. This means that if you are injured, you are covered regardless of who caused the injury or the circumstances. Whether you are hurt at work, playing sport, in a car accident, or tripping over at home, ACC covers the costs of your treatment and rehabilitation. In exchange for this universal cover, New Zealanders gave up the right to sue for compensatory damages for personal injury (with limited exceptions). This trade-off means that injured people receive support quickly without lengthy and uncertain court processes.
        </p>

        <p>
          ACC is funded through a combination of levies paid by different groups. Employees pay the Earner's Levy, employers pay the Work Levy and Working Safer Levy, vehicle owners pay the Motor Vehicle Levy (through vehicle licensing), and the government contributes for non-earners through the Non-Earners' Account. Each levy funds a different part of the ACC scheme, reflecting the different sources of injury risk.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">The ACC Earner's Levy Rate</h2>

        <p>
          For the 2025-2026 tax year (1 April 2025 to 31 March 2026), the ACC Earner's Levy is set at $1.60 per $100 of liable earnings, which is equivalent to a rate of 1.60 percent. This rate is set by the government and reviewed annually. The rate has varied over the years; it was $1.39 per $100 for 2022-2023, $1.53 for 2023-2024, and $1.60 for the current year.
        </p>

        <p>
          The levy is calculated on your gross earnings before tax. It applies to all earnings from employment, including salary, wages, bonuses, overtime, commissions, and most other forms of employee remuneration. The levy is deducted by your employer alongside PAYE tax and remitted to IRD, which passes it on to ACC.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">The Maximum Liable Earnings Cap</h2>

        <p>
          An important feature of the ACC Earner's Levy is that it is capped at a maximum level of earnings. For 2025-2026, the maximum liable earnings figure is approximately $142,283. This means that if you earn more than $142,283, you only pay the levy on the first $142,283 of your earnings. Any income above this cap does not attract additional ACC levy.
        </p>

        <p>
          At the 1.60 percent rate, the maximum annual ACC Earner's Levy works out to approximately $2,276.53. Once you reach this cap during the tax year, no further levy is deducted from your pay for the remainder of the year. However, because the levy is typically calculated on each pay period's earnings extrapolated to an annual equivalent, the cap may be applied gradually throughout the year rather than as a sudden cutoff.
        </p>

        <p>
          The earnings cap exists because ACC benefits are also capped. If you are injured and unable to work, ACC's weekly compensation is based on 80 percent of your pre-injury earnings, but only up to the maximum liable earnings figure. Higher earners who want income protection above the ACC cap need to arrange private income protection insurance separately.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">How the Levy Appears on Your Payslip</h2>

        <p>
          On your payslip, the ACC Earner's Levy typically appears as a separate line item under deductions, alongside PAYE, KiwiSaver, and any student loan repayments. Some payroll systems label it "ACC Earner's Levy", while others may abbreviate it to "ACC Levy" or simply "ACC". The deduction is calculated for each pay period based on your gross earnings.
        </p>

        <p>
          For an employee earning $70,000 per year paid fortnightly, the ACC levy per fortnight would be approximately $70,000 divided by 26 fortnights equals $2,692.31 gross pay per fortnight, multiplied by 1.60 percent equals approximately $43.08 per fortnight. Over the full year, this adds up to approximately $1,120.
        </p>

        <p>
          Here are some annual ACC Earner's Levy amounts at different income levels for the 2025-2026 year:
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
          <table class="w-full border-collapse border border-border text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-surface-alt">
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Annual Income</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Annual ACC Levy</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Fortnightly Deduction</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$40,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$640.00</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$24.62</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$60,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$960.00</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$36.92</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$80,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$1,280.00</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$49.23</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$100,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$1,600.00</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$61.54</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$142,283+</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$2,276.53 (max)</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$87.56</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">What ACC Covers</h2>

        <p>
          ACC provides a remarkably comprehensive range of cover for personal injuries. The key entitlements include payment for medical treatment such as doctor's visits, specialist consultations, surgery, and hospital stays. ACC also covers physiotherapy, chiropractic care, osteopathy, and other rehabilitation services. Prescription costs related to an injury are covered, and ACC can fund modifications to your home or vehicle if needed for your recovery.
        </p>

        <p>
          If your injury prevents you from working, ACC provides weekly compensation at 80 percent of your pre-injury weekly earnings, starting from the second week after the injury (your employer covers the first week at 80 percent of your relevant daily pay). This weekly compensation continues until you can return to work or until ACC determines you have reached your maximum level of recovery. For serious injuries, this support can continue for many years.
        </p>

        <p>
          ACC also covers lump-sum compensation for permanent impairment, funeral grants for fatal injuries, and support for dependants of people who die as a result of an injury. The scheme covers injuries sustained anywhere in the world, so if you are injured while travelling overseas, you can still access ACC support for your treatment and rehabilitation when you return to New Zealand.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">The Employer's ACC Obligations</h2>

        <p>
          While the Earner's Levy is deducted from your pay, your employer also has ACC obligations of their own. Employers pay an ACC Work Levy, the rate of which depends on their industry's risk classification. Industries with higher rates of workplace injuries, such as construction, forestry, and manufacturing, pay higher levies than lower-risk industries like office-based services. Employers also pay the Working Safer Levy, a flat-rate levy that funds workplace health and safety activities.
        </p>

        <p>
          In the first week after an employee is injured and unable to work, the employer is responsible for paying weekly compensation at 80 percent of the employee's relevant daily pay. From the second week onwards, ACC takes over this responsibility. Employers are also required to keep a workplace injury register and report serious workplace injuries to WorkSafe New Zealand.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">ACC for Self-Employed Workers</h2>

        <p>
          Self-employed individuals have different ACC obligations compared to employees. In addition to the Earner's Levy, self-employed workers pay a Work Levy based on their industry classification. The combined levies for a self-employed person can be significantly higher than the Earner's Levy alone, particularly in higher-risk industries. Self-employed ACC levies are invoiced directly by ACC rather than being deducted through the PAYE system.
        </p>

        <p>
          Self-employed workers can also choose their ACC CoverPlus Extra level, which allows them to nominate their level of income cover. This is important because otherwise, ACC bases weekly compensation on the previous year's liable earnings, which may not reflect current income. CoverPlus Extra provides certainty about the level of cover you have and the levies you pay, making it easier to budget for this cost.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">How to Make an ACC Claim</h2>

        <p>
          Making an ACC claim in New Zealand is straightforward. In most cases, your healthcare provider (doctor, physiotherapist, hospital, or other registered provider) lodges the claim on your behalf when you seek treatment for an injury. You do not need to fill in separate claim forms in most cases. Your provider assesses your injury, provides treatment, and notifies ACC, which then registers the claim and covers the treatment costs.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you need ongoing treatment or support, ACC assigns a case manager to coordinate your care and rehabilitation. You may need to attend follow-up appointments, undergo assessments, or participate in rehabilitation programmes as part of your recovery plan. ACC aims to support your return to work and daily life as quickly and safely as possible.
        </p>

        <p>
          If your claim is declined, you have the right to review the decision. You can request a review through ACC's internal review process, and if you are still dissatisfied, you can appeal to the District Court. Independent advocacy services are available to help claimants navigate the review and appeals process.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">ACC and Private Health Insurance</h2>

        <p>
          New Zealand's ACC scheme covers personal injuries, but it does not cover illness or disease. This is an important distinction. If you develop an illness such as cancer, heart disease, or a chronic condition, ACC does not provide cover. For illness-related costs, you rely on the public health system or private health insurance. Many New Zealanders hold private health insurance alongside ACC to cover illness-related treatment, shorter wait times for elective surgery, and access to private hospitals and specialists.
        </p>

        <p>
          For high earners whose income exceeds the ACC cap, private income protection insurance can supplement ACC's weekly compensation to maintain a higher level of income replacement if they are unable to work due to injury. Some employers include income protection insurance as part of their employee benefits package.
        </p>

        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 not-prose">
          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              Is the ACC Earner's Levy the only ACC levy I pay?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">As an employee, the Earner's Levy is the only ACC levy deducted from your pay. Your employer also pays a separate ACC Work Levy and a Working Safer Levy, but these are business costs and do not appear on your payslip. If you are self-employed, you pay both the Earner's Levy and a Work Levy based on your industry's risk classification.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              Can I opt out of ACC?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">No, you cannot opt out of the ACC scheme. It is a compulsory, universal system that covers everyone in New Zealand, including visitors. The Earner's Levy is a mandatory deduction from your pay. In return, you receive comprehensive no-fault personal injury cover regardless of how or where an injury occurs.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              What does ACC cover in New Zealand?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">ACC covers the costs of treatment and rehabilitation for personal injuries, regardless of how they happened. This includes workplace injuries, sports injuries, accidents at home, car accidents, and more. ACC pays for medical treatment, surgery, physiotherapy, prescriptions, and other rehabilitation costs. If you cannot work due to your injury, ACC provides weekly compensation at 80% of your pre-injury earnings (up to a cap) after the first week.</p>
          </details>
        </div>

